ğŸ” Requirements:
The object inside try (...) must implement AutoCloseable â€” which StructuredTaskScope does!



ğŸ§  Why do we use it with StructuredTaskScope?
===============================================
Here's what happens:
try (var scope = new StructuredTaskScope.ShutdownOnFailure()) {
    ...
}

âœ… A new scope (ShutdownOnFailure) is created.
âœ… Tasks are forked (submitted) within the scope.
âœ… When the block ends:
	If everything succeeded: the scope exits cleanly.
	If anything failed: the scope automatically cancels remaining tasks.
âœ… The scope is closed automatically â€” no manual cleanup required.
âœ… Auto-close: Scope shuts down automatically when the block exits

This protects against:
	Thread leaks
	Dangling tasks
	Uncaught exceptions